{"title":"PinnerSage: Multi-Modal User Embedding Framework for Recommendations at Pinterest","domain":"IR_REC","seeds":[{"problem":"Single user-embedding approaches collapse a user’s multiple, evolving interests into one vector, limiting relevance and diversity; prior multi-embedding methods often fix the number of embeddings or are hard to serve at scale.","method":"PinnerSage clusters each user’s recent action pins in a fixed multimodal item-embedding space (PinSage integrates visual, text, and graph signals) using Ward hierarchical clustering, which automatically determines the number of concept-coherent clusters. Each cluster is represented by a medoid pin (not a centroid) to avoid topic drift, improve robustness to outliers, and enable lightweight storage/caching via pin IDs. A time-decayed importance score per cluster guides sampling of up to three medoids per request; their embeddings query an ANN index to retrieve candidates. This removes constraints on the number of per-user embeddings and couples medoid sampling with decayed importance to track recency and frequency."},{"problem":"Nearest-neighbor candidate retrieval over billions of items must be accurate and cost/latency-efficient; naive indexing returns near-duplicates and is expensive to serve.","method":"The system adopts HNSW for ANN indexing of pin embeddings, which outperforms LSH Orthoplex on cost/latency/recall. It refines the candidate pool by filtering near-duplicates and low-quality pins, and caches queries at the medoid pin-ID level (rather than raw embedding vectors). Together these choices significantly cut serving cost (e.g., ~60% vs LSH, ~50% via index refinement, ~75% from medoid caching) while maintaining high-recall retrieval."},{"problem":"User interests shift in real time, but recomputing full multi-embedding profiles continuously at web scale is infeasible; systems must balance long-term preferences with fast adaptation.","method":"PinnerSage employs a two-pronged serving architecture: a daily batch MapReduce job clusters the last 90 days of actions to produce medoids and time-decayed importance scores stored in a key-value store, while a lightweight online component incrementally updates clusters using the user’s most recent actions streamed in real time (e.g., last ~20). The batch and online outputs are combined, and updated importance scores steer medoid sampling for retrieval, yielding both responsiveness and long-term stability."}]}
